04140nam a22006015i 9780271091013DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710910137 a10.1515/97802710910132doi  a(DE-B1597)586185  a(OCoLC)1262307614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0540002bisacsh1 aMartin, A. Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlcohol, Violence, and Disorder in Traditional Europe /cA. Lynn Martin. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 The Problem of Alcohol and Violence -- tChapter 2 The Condemnations of the Moralists -- tChapter 3 The Consumption of Alcohol -- tChapter 4 Recreational Drinking -- tChapter 5 Disorder: Places -- tChapter 6 Disorder: Persons -- tChapter 7 Violence -- tChapter 8 Regulations -- tChapter 9 Alcohol, Violence, & Disorder -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Author -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditional Europe had high levels of violence and of alcohol consumption, both higher than they are in modern Western societies, where studies demonstrate a link between violence and alcohol. A. Lynn Martin uses an anthropological approach to examine drinking, drinking establishments, violence, and disorder, and compares the wine-producing south with the beer-drinking north and Catholic France and Italy with Protestant England, and explores whether alcohol consumption can also explain the violence and disorder of traditional Europe.Both Catholic and Protestant moralists believed in the link, and they condemned drunkenness and drinking establishments for causing violence and disorder. They did not advocate complete abstinence, however, for alcoholic beverages had an important role in most people&apos;s diets. Less appreciated by the moralists was alcohol&apos;s function as the ubiquitous social lubricant and the increasing importance of alehouses and taverns as centers of popular recreation.The study utilizes both quantitative and qualitative evidence from a wide variety of sources to question the beliefs of the moralists and the assumptions of modern scholars about the role of alcohol and drinking establishments in causing violence and disorder. It ends by analyzing the often-conflicting regulations of local, regional, and national governments that attempted to ensure that their citizens had a reliable supply of good drink at a reasonable cost but also to control who drank what, where, when, and how.No other comparable book examines the relationship of alcohol to violence and disorder during this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271091013zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271091013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271091013.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK